{"type":"message","id":"0e72eafb","parentId":"862e0ed6","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:52:00.044Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user says it's not the thinking block issue. Let me dig deeper. The problem is that every response is slow since Apr 14. Let me check what specifically changed around Apr 14 that could affect response latency.\n\nLooking at what I know:\n1. The gateway process (PID 503055) has CPU 13.1% and memory 620MB\n2. There are 100+ child sessions in this main session - that's a LOT\n3. The session is \"running\" (status: running)\n4. Total tokens: 24860, contextTokens: 204800 (context window is almost full!)\n\nWait - the context is at 204800 tokens. \n\nThat's basically maxed out. With the context window nearly exhausted, every response requires the model to process the entire conversation history, which would explain the slowdown. But this is a cumulative effect from this session alone - if the user is saying responses became slow after Apr 14 regardless of session resets, then something else changed in the system around that time. Let me think about what could have been modified on Apr 14 specifically.\n\nLooking at the session data, I notice `thinkingLevel: \"adaptive\"` is set. The Apr 14 changes included a revision to SOUL.md v10.1 that might have altered how thinking is configured by default. But the user mentioned `/new` resets should give fresh sessions with default settings, yet they're still experiencing slowness even then - so it's not just a context buildup issue. I should examine whether something in the bootstrap process itself changed on that date, or look at whether there's a specific model configuration that's causing this.\n\nThe bootstrap hook loads session summaries and memory files when a new session starts, so if those files are large or the hook has additional processing logic, it could be adding latency. The user's complaint is that responses have been slow ever since the Apr 14 update, regardless of session resets - this points to something persistent in the environment or configuration that changed on that date. The session summary files being loaded at startup could be adding latency if they're large. I'm also wondering if the bootstrap process is doing something heavier than before—maybe scanning more files or running additional hooks. The model choice itself might be the culprit: if it switched from a faster model to something like MiniMax-M2.7, that could explain the slowdown independent of the thinking block changes. I'm wondering if the bootstrap process itself is the culprit—if it's loading significantly more files now, that could add noticeable overhead before the first response. Let me check whether session context files are being loaded unnecessarily, or if there's something else being initialized during bootstrap that's causing the delay.\n\nThe wiki-learn cron jobs firing hourly could be consuming CPU and I/O resources, though that shouldn't directly impact the bootstrap sequence. I'm also thinking about whether the 3105 classifier might be introducing latency in the routing pipeline. The classifier's response time has been variable—ranging from 134ms to much longer—and if it's being called for every round trip, those delays could accumulate. But the user confirmed this happens every round, not just during /new sessions, so it's likely not a bootstrap issue at all.\n\nLooking at the session list output, I'm seeing something concerning: there are over 100 child sessions in the current session, which means there's a massive amount of conversation history being maintained. Even though the context window shows 204800 tokens, those child sessions might be creating some kind of processing overhead. I need to understand what these child sessions actually are—they could be sub-agents spawned during the AXS code review that were never properly cleaned up. That would definitely slow down every response. But the user said they already tried /new and it's still slow, which suggests the issue might be something else entirely.\n\nLet me check if the model itself changed. The session is using MiniMax-M2.7, but maybe the system defaulted to a slower model after the April 14 update. I should ask them to run /status to see what the current configuration actually is. I'm also wondering if the thinking=adaptive setting might be configured to use a slower model when certain conditions are met. And I should verify whether the 3105 classifier is performing poorly—it took 134ms earlier, which seems acceptable, but I need to check if it's been much slower recently. Let me also look at whether there were any config file changes around April 14.\n\nI think the best approach is to check the config files directly to see what changed, and ask the user to run /status to see the current model configuration. If the thinking=adaptive setting is configured to use a slower model, that could be the culprit. Let me look at the gateway config files and check for any recent changes.\n\nI should also examine the session context more carefully—if the context window is near capacity at 204800 tokens, that would significantly degrade performance. And if the thinking=adaptive config was changed to use a slower model like ollama/qwen2.5:14b instead of the default MiniMax, that would definitely cause the slowdown.\n\nLooking at the thinking levels available—off, light, adaptive, deep, and maximum—I need to understand what \"adaptive\" actually maps to in this system. The user mentioned the behavior changed after April 14th, so the thinking level configuration itself might have shifted, or how it selects the thinking approach could have been modified.\n\nIf \"adaptive\" is triggering deeper reasoning modes, that would explain the slowdown. Let me check what the current configuration actually specifies for this setting.\n\nWait, I'm realizing something important about the channel latency issue. The user initially thought messages were delayed because nothing appeared until they updated, but when they said \"you lie,\" that message came through immediately. So the channel itself seems to be working fine now. If the user is still experiencing slowness despite this working message, the problem isn't the channel delivery anymore—it might be that they perceive responses as slow because the thinking block is visible, or there's something else causing actual delays in how I'm generating responses.\n\nLet me reconsider what could have changed on April 14th. I should examine the gateway configuration more carefully, and I'm noticing the session has accumulated 100+ child sessions. If each response needs to manage state across all those sessions, that could be creating overhead. I'm also wondering if there's a cron job running that might be consuming resources or interfering with response generation.\n\nLooking at the system more carefully, I see several cron jobs are configured - there's memory maintenance, memory keeper, and wiki learn tasks. While these shouldn't directly slow down responses, the wiki-learn cron specifically runs every hour and might be consuming CPU. Let me check what the current cron configuration actually specifies.\n\nThe most likely culprit though is the thinking configuration itself. The thinking block itself might be the problem - if it's set to \"adaptive\" and that triggers deep reasoning, the visible thinking could be what's making responses feel slow to the user. Let me look at what changed with thinking in the SOUL.md updates from April 14th.\n\nI'm also wondering if the bootstrap process itself is loading more files now. The session context shows classification and scoring metadata that was injected before I received the message, which suggests the v8 router processed it. If the classification took 134ms, that means it was waiting for that round-trip before I could respond, so the bottleneck might be in that classification step rather than in my actual response generation.\n\nLet me look at the session transcript to see if there's something else going on, or if there's a cron job firing that's adding latency.","thinkingSignature":"021c8f5d31de5ed1ad0f4122f88132bf4bc3136f20ce385e0cfbf043f93bc391"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n好，排除 thinking block。继续挖。\n\n让我查一下 gateway 的配置和实际运行状态，看看是不是 4.14 之后哪个默认参数变了：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d953728573054d1fa36f9e71","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw -name \"*.yaml\" -o -name \"*.yml\" -o -name \"*.json\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | grep -v \".git\" | head -30"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fa03fe21e66e4b5baee134eb","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/gateway.json 2>/dev/null || cat ~/.openclaw/gateway.yaml 2>/dev/null || echo \"no gateway config found\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":265,"output":1677,"cacheRead":42880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":44822,"cost":{"input":0.0000795,"output":0.0020123999999999997,"cacheRead":0.0025727999999999997,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004664699999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776343880176,"responseId":"06300e472aac1e2a09f26238337ea2c5"}}
