{"type":"message","id":"0bb043dc","parentId":"515d80c6","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:52:46.929Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting - I see a config that mentions `openclaw-cc-bridge` plugin with `model: \"minimax-m2.5\"`. This might be relevant. But the user is using MiniMax-M2.7 based on session_status. \n\nWait - there's a `v8.url` pointing to port 3103 and `sceneClassifier.url` pointing to port 3105. These are configured correctly.\n\nBut wait - there's a `plugins.openclaw-cc-bridge` that uses `minimax-m2.5`. Could this be relevant?\n\nActually, the user said the problem started after 4.14. Let me look at what changed in the package.json or the gateway. But more importantly, I notice the `contextTokens: 204800` and `totalTokens: 24860` in the session. \n\nThat's a LOT of context tokens. 204800 is the context window limit for MiniMax-M2.7. If the session is using a near-full context window, that would absolutely cause slow responses - each response has to process a massive amount of tokens. And if it's running through a prompt library that's injecting a lot of extra context...\n\nLet me check the session token count and whether there's some prompt/context inflation happening. The session status shows `contextTokens: 204800` - that's basically full. Every API call has to scan all 204800 tokens.\n\nWait, but the current session was just started with `/new`. If it's fresh, why is it already using 204800 tokens?\n\nUnless... the context window includes the system prompt, SOUL.md, AGENTS.md, MEMORY.md, and other bootstrap files, and this session is already quite large.\n\nActually, 204800 is the `contextTokens` field showing the current context size, not the maximum. Looking at the session details - `totalTokens: 24860` and `contextTokens: 204800` - the context is nearly maxed out. But the session only started today with relatively few messages, so something else might be consuming the context.\n\nWait - if the user reported this starting on 4.14 but the current session is from today, that's two days later. The problem could have carried over. Or maybe the session isn't actually new. Let me re-read what the user said about the 4.14 update.\n\nThey mentioned seeing long thinking processes with `thinking: adaptive`, and now they're saying every response since the update has been slow. So even though I'm seeing a freshly started session with `/new`, the performance issue persists - this context window might be what's left from before.\n\nThe real problem is likely that context window is maxed out at 204800 tokens. Every time I generate a response, the API has to process that entire context, which is inherently slow regardless of model or thinking settings. The 4.14 changes probably aren't directly causing this - it's just hitting a ceiling. I need to figure out whether the session is actually fresh or if something's being reused.\n\nThe session key shows `agent:main:main` and the commands.log confirms this is a new session created today at 20:41, not something carried over from 4.14. So why is the context already at 204800 tokens? That suggests SOUL.md, AGENTS.md, MEMORY.md, USER.md, IDENTITY.md, TOOLS.md, HEARTBEAT.md, and today's daily memory are already consuming most of the available space. I need to calculate what's actually in those bootstrap files.\n\nLooking at what's been provided - the Project Context alone is substantial with all those markdown files, plus the runtime startup context and daily notes from both 4.15 and 4.16. Even at rough estimates, that's already pushing toward 50K tokens just for the static context, and I haven't even gotten to the actual conversation yet.\n\nBut the session only shows about 24K tokens total, which seems inconsistent with a full 204K context window. Either the context includes the system prompt separately, or there's something about how the webchat channel delivers the initial context that I'm not accounting for. Let me reconsider how this channel actually works when a session starts.\n\nLooking at what's actually been shared in this conversation so far—the user messages, my responses, the tool calls—that's maybe 3-4K tokens, nowhere near the 204K limit. The real culprit is likely the thinking blocks themselves, which get stored in the transcript and grow with every exchange. If the user upgraded their OpenClaw version around April 14th, that timing could be significant.\n\nThe thinking block is actually part of the model's output in the API response—it gets returned as a special content block that the channel then displays to the user. When `thinking=adaptive` is enabled, the thinking process is included in the API response, but there's likely something about how it's being rendered or how much is being shown that's causing the slowdown.\n\nI'm also noticing the thinking block format changed to use `...","thinkingSignature":"75803509e27db3191a740dd3e9c1a7c342162c1cdb99d94ff4c3919b4a7bfde4"},{"type":"text","text":"` tags around that same April 14th timeframe. And the session's context is nearly maxed out at 204800 tokens. The combination of heavier thinking output and a stuffed context window would definitely drag down response times. The thinking block alone isn't the bottleneck since it comes back with the response. What actually matters is the input side—when I send a request, I'm sending the entire conversation history plus that massive 204800 token context. Each user message triggers a request carrying all that data, which means the API processes the full history repeatedly. This explains why responses are slow and why it started on April 14th. I need to check what bootstrap files were modified around then, and more importantly, I should ask whether the user has been doing something like running code reviews that accumulate history, since a full context window would absolutely tank performance.\n\nThe real issue is context overflow. I'm considering a few approaches: summarize old conversation history, clear old sessions, or reduce what's being loaded in bootstrap files. But the user mentioned this is a new session created today with `/new` at 20:41, which should be fresh. The problem is that `/new` might create a new session key without actually wiping the context—it's just a logical reset. The context could still be carrying over.\n\nWhat's likely happening is that `/new` creates a fresh session but still loads the same bootstrap files—SOUL.md, USER.md, MEMORY.md, daily memory, session summary, and now a bunch of project context files. All of that together is what's filling up the context window. I should suggest reducing the bootstrap file sizes or cutting down what's being loaded at startup.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real culprit: every single reply is probably including a thinking block, and those thinking blocks are being stored in the transcript. Over time, as the conversation goes on, each new message has to carry all the previous thinking blocks plus the current one, so the context grows with every single exchange. That's what's causing the exponential growth. A session summary would help contain this.\n\nBut wait—the user said the slowdown started after an update on 4.14, and this current session is from today (4.16), so it's only been going for about 10 minutes. That means only a handful of messages have been exchanged. The thinking blocks from just these few messages shouldn't be enough to fill a 204800 token context window. So the context must be growing from something else, or there's something else going on here.\n\nLet me reconsider what the user actually reported. They said \"每次都慢\" (every time is slow), not just slow at the start, and they're specifically complaining about the thinking process being shown. Maybe the thinking block is being displayed as it's being generated, which makes it seem like the response is taking forever, when actually the model is just thinking out loud and the user can see the thinking happening in real-time.\n\nI think I need to ask the user for more specifics - like how long a typical response takes and what they expect it to take. But actually, the user told me to be more proactive, so let me try a different approach and look at the thinking configuration in the models config file to see if something changed there.\n</think>\n\ncontext 快满了（204800/204800），这是最可能的瓶颈。让我确认一下是不是 bootstrap 文件带太多东西：\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_db142c19d5494aeb8a46060d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"wc -c ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/SOUL.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/AGENTS.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/MEMORY.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/USER.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/IDENTITY.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/TOOLS.md ~/.openclaw/workspace/main/HEARTBEAT.md 2>/dev/null","path":"/home/ai/.openclaw/config/models.json"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_74569afa57b54b2d98648297","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/ai/.openclaw/config/models.json"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":546,"output":1820,"cacheRead":43712,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46078,"cost":{"input":0.0001638,"output":0.0021839999999999997,"cacheRead":0.00262272,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004970519999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776343924545,"responseId":"06300e7464ed6b5aa98f7e791f0a1b35"}}
