{"type":"message","id":"2875c94e","parentId":"ce62c2eb","timestamp":"2026-04-16T14:36:49.317Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the agents/main/sessions directory is 132MB with many session files. The current session's transcript is 0f11a8d7-e561-410d-8190-af6983db94f2.jsonl (334KB) - that's the subagent that timed out.\n\nThe session list from the API earlier showed `agent:main:main` has 142 childSessions. These are the subagent sessions. Every time a message comes in, the gateway might be iterating through these child sessions for some reason.\n\nLet me look at the openclaw.log to find errors or warnings around the time of the slowdown.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be simpler. The Control UI uses WebSocket to connect to the gateway. But looking at the connections:\n\n\n- Port 3102 only has 4 connections total (2 on IPv4, 2 on IPv6)\n- But the gateway process (pid 503055) shows CPU 13.1% and memory 620MB\n\nThat CPU usage is consistently elevated, which makes sense given all the background wiki-ingest.py processes running every hour. The gateway itself seems to be working harder than expected.\n\nI should check the gateway's WebSocket connection handler to see how it manages sessions and whether client polling is involved. Actually, let me step back and reconsider what we know: messages take 5 seconds to 1 minute to deliver, which points to either message batching or queueing on the gateway side, or possibly the polling interval on the client. Since the Control UI communicates with the gateway via WebSocket at 3102, I need to understand how that connection handles message delivery. The system operates as a black box, but the user has confirmed the latency started after upgrading to 4.14 on April 14th. Looking at potential causes: the context engine compact logic only triggers on tool-loop deltas, so it shouldn't fire every turn, but the gateway session fix preventing metadata overwrites could be adding processing overhead. The markdown-it replacement shouldn't be a factor since the webchat sends plain text to the gateway rather than rendering markdown on the gateway side.\n\nThe most suspicious change is the Control UI's markdown-it update which replaced marked.js—this affects how the UI renders messages, but if the bottleneck is in message submission latency rather than rendering speed, that's probably not it. I should focus on whether 4.14 introduced a behavioral change in how the gateway processes or queues messages, since the changelog mentions both \"compact engine-owned sessions from the first tool-loop delta\" and a fix for heartbeat/cron/exec-event turns overwriting shared-session routing.\n\nLooking at the gateway startup log, it was restarted on April 15 at 04:40:50 and has been running continuously since then, so the current slowness isn't from a stale process.\n\nThe real issue might be that after the gateway restart, the Control UI is maintaining 142 child sessions—likely from yesterday's parallel subagent work—and the session serialization could be creating a bottleneck. Though 142 subagents shouldn't cause a noticeable delay unless there's an O(n²) operation somewhere in the session management.\n\nThe 5-second-to-1-minute latency range suggests something is queued or waiting rather than a fixed polling interval. This points to either the Control UI using long-polling with the server holding the request until a message arrives (which would be 5-60 seconds), or messages sitting in a gateway queue before being processed. The IPv6 connection with recv-q of 90 bytes might indicate the server is buffering data before sending it.\n\nLooking at the gateway API, it serves the Control UI HTML on port 3102, and the WebSocket connection for real-time messaging goes to the same port. The long-polling approach would manifest as the UI making requests that wait for messages, whereas WebSocket would receive pushes immediately. If the recv-q shows 90 bytes sitting in the kernel buffer, that's data already received by the gateway but not yet consumed by the application—which could explain the delay between when messages arrive at the gateway and when they're actually delivered to the UI.\n\nBut I should step back and consider what's actually changed. The user mentioned everything worked fine before April 14th, then got slow after that update. Rather than continuing to trace through the connection state, I should ask directly: does restarting the gateway or updating the package resolve this? Though I can't restart services without the user's approval.\n\nLet me try checking the gateway health endpoint to see if there's something obvious there.","thinkingSignature":"e5d23fbdce243b4abc3a1417ce3e02d050be5c0c1281e0720ad8cc2bfba41b1f"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n抱歉让你等了。subagent 全部超时，代码库太大+编译后 JS 难读。\n\n直接说结论——根据我这 1.5 小时的分析，**最可能的根因**：\n\n**4.14 的 `Gateway/sessions` 改动导致 session metadata 写入变频繁**\n\n4.14 changelog 提到：\n> \"stop heartbeat, cron-event, and exec-event turns from overwriting shared-session routing and origin metadata\"\n\n这个改动让 session 的 lifecycle 事件广播更频繁。Control UI 每次收到 `sessions.changed` 事件都要重新 fetch session 列表——如果你的 session 有 142 个 childSessions，每次更新都要 diff 一遍，可能产生延迟。\n\n**但这只是推测，最快验证方式：**\n\n重启 gateway 看看是否恢复：\n\n```\nopenclaw gateway restart\n```\n\n如果重启后回复正常，说明是运行时状态累积的问题（比如 142 个 childSession 的序列化开销）。如果重启后还是慢，说明是 4.14 代码本身的行为变化。\n\n要我帮你执行 restart 吗？"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1278,"output":1123,"cacheRead":78912,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":81313,"cost":{"input":0.0003834,"output":0.0013476,"cacheRead":0.0047347199999999996,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0064657199999999995}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776350188387,"responseId":"063026eb589d4bd3f4365d5242312960"}}
